entry.title: Flash Flood Warning issued September 17 at 5:02AM MDT until September 17 at 8:00AM MDT by NWS Albuquerque NM
entry.summary:
FFWABQ
The National Weather Service in Albuquerque has issued a
* Flash Flood Warning for... Central Harding County in northeastern New Mexico... Northeastern San Miguel County in northeastern New Mexico...
* Until 800 AM MDT.
* At 502 AM MDT, Doppler radar indicated thunderstorms producing heavy rain persisting between Conchas, Trujillo, Mosquero and Bueyeros. Between 1.25 and 2.5 inches of rain have fallen. Additional rainfall amounts of 0.5 to 1.5 inches are possible in the warned area. Flash flooding is ongoing or expected to begin shortly and is most likely in the vicinity of Mosquero.
HAZARD...Flash flooding caused by thunderstorms.
SOURCE...Radar indicated.
IMPACT...Flash flooding of small creeks and streams, urban areas, highways, streets and underpasses as well as other poor drainage and low-lying areas.
* Some locations that will experience flash flooding include... Mosquero, Solano and Bell Ranch.
Monitoring message only. Please disregard.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued September 17 at 4:50AM CDT by NWS Green Bay WI
entry.summary:
Patchy fog, locally dense with visibilities from one-quarter to one-half of a mile, were impacting locations close to the lakeshore.
Where fog persists, it should lift shortly after sunrise. Until then, the fog will result in locally hazardous driving conditions.
When driving in fog, slow down, use your low beam headlights and keep a safe distance from other vehicles as the visibility may change rapidly in a short distance. Allow extra time to reach your destination.

entry.title: Hydrologic Outlook issued September 17 at 3:12AM MDT by NWS Great Falls MT
entry.summary:
ESFTFX
A strong early fall storm system will spread an increasing coverage of showers and thunderstorms into the area this afternoon and evening with widespread rain developing tonight and continuing into Wednesday afternoon before gradually diminishing from west to east Wednesday night.
Brief heavy rainfall is possible with thunderstorms this evening with a more widespread coverage of moderate to locally heavy rain developing tonight through Wednesday morning. Total rainfall amounts in excess of one inch are expected across much of north-central Montana east of I-15 with probabilities for rainfall amounts in excess of two inches ranging from 40% to 60% across much of Judith Basin, Fergus, Chouteau and Blaine counties. Highest rainfall totals will likely occur in the immediate vicinity of the Little Belt, Highwood and Big Snowy mountains where there is a 30% chance of rainfall amounts exceeding 3 inches.
Local flooding concerns may arise in flood prone areas and in areas near terrain where heavier rain is most persistent as well as some urban and rural areas with poor drainage.

entry.title: Flood Advisory issued September 17 at 4:58AM EDT until September 17 at 8:00AM EDT by NWS Greenville-Spartanburg SC
entry.summary:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by excessive rainfall continues.
* WHERE...Northwestern Union County, North Carolina.
* WHEN...Until 800 AM EDT.
* IMPACTS...Nuisance flooding of low-lying areas adjacent to streams and other poor-drainage areas, including farmland, parks, greenways, boat-access areas, golf courses, underpasses, and parking lots. Isolated, shallow flows over roadways is possible. A few flood-prone, low-water crossings may become impassible. A small culvert washout or two is possible.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS... - At 446 AM EDT, Doppler radar and automated rain gauges indicate that the heaviest rain bands from a weak coastal low have moved well to the west of Union County. Additional heavy rainfall is not expected for this event. Widespread 2.5-3.5" accumulations occurred across the county in about 6 hours last night, resulting in excessive runoff and rapid rises on area streams. Several streams exceeded bankfull conditions, and several streamgauges exceeded Action Stage, resulting in nuisance flooding of adjacent low-lying areas. While floodwaters have receded in much of the county, out-of- bank coniditions are persisting in the north and south forks of Crooked Creek near Hemby Bridge, generally near Poplin Rd, Ridge Rd, Unionville-Indian Trail Rd, Indian Trail-Fairview Rd, Idlewild Rd, and Rocky River Rd. Nuisance flooding of farmland, woodlands, parks, and greenways will persist in the Crooked Creek watershed for the next 3-6 hours. Therefore, the Flood Advisory will remain in effect until floodwaters recede across the northwestern part of Union County and has been cancelled for the remainder of the county.
- Some locations that may continue to experience flooding include... Indian Trail, Stallings, Unionville, Lake Park, Hemby Bridge, and Fairview. - http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued September 16 at 8:45PM AKDT by NWS Anchorage AK
entry.summary:
A strengthening storm system moves over the Pribilof Islands from Monday afternoon through Tuesday night. While the front will bring southeasterly winds and rain to the eastern Aleutians and Alaska Peninsula beginning Monday afternoon, the strongest winds and highest seas will occur as winds wrap back around the low Tuesday morning.
Southwesterly to westerly wind gusts of 55 to 65 mph and wave heights of 15 to 25 ft are expected for the eastern Aleutians, Alaska Peninsula, and Bering side coastal waters for much of tomorrow. Wind gusts could approach 70 mph around Cold Bay and Unimak Island Wednesday afternoon and evening.
Wave heights building to 15 ft are expected for the outer half of Unalaska Bay late Tuesday morning through late Tuesday night.

entry.title: Air Quality Alert issued September 16 at 3:08PM PDT by NWS San Diego CA
entry.summary:
The South Coast AQMD has issued an air quality alert due to increased particle pollution from blowing dust. The air quality alert is in effect until 9 AM Tuesday.
In areas directly impacted by high levels of windblown dust, limit your exposure by remaining indoors with windows and doors closed and avoiding vigorous physical activity. Run your air conditioner or an air purifier. If temperatures allow, avoid using whole house fans or swamp coolers that bring in outside air.
Exposure to high particle pollution levels can cause serious health problems, including asthma attacks, heart and lung disease symptoms, and increased risk of respiratory infections. People with heart or lung diseases should follow their doctor's advice for dealing with episodes of unhealthy air quality. Children, older adults, and people with respiratory or heart disease should avoid prolonged exposure and strenuous activities when particle pollution levels are high.
Levels of particle pollution can vary hour by hour and by location depending on wind conditions.
For the latest air quality forecasts and information, visit the website at aqmd.gov.

entry.title: High Surf Advisory issued September 16 at 10:07AM AKDT until September 18 at 10:00AM AKDT by NWS Anchorage AK
entry.summary:
The National Weather Service in Anchorage has issued a High Surf Advisory, which is in effect from 10 PM Tuesday to 10 AM AKDT Wednesday.
* LOCATION...Primarily for the southern Bristol Bay coastline from the mouth of the Kvichak River to Port Heiden, including the communities of Naknek, Egegik, and Pilot Point. High surf is possible but less likely from the mouth of the Kvichak River west to Cape Newenham.
* WINDS AND WAVES...Southwesterly winds of 30 to 40 mph are expected, with gusts as high as 50 to 65 mph. Waves up to 10 feet breaking on the shoreline.
* TIMING...Strong southwesterly winds peak between about 10pm Tuesday and 6am Wednesday, around the same time as high tide. The worst conditions will occur around or shortly after midnight, then improve through the early morning hours on Wednesday.
* IMPACTS...Winds and waves are forecast to bring about a 4 to 6 ft surge on top of the high tide, which may inundate or move property along the shoreline. Coastal erosion during high tide is likely.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...While the strongest winds are expected for the southern Bristol Bay coastline, a long duration of south to southwesterly winds from Tuesday morning through evening could also lead to high surf along the northern Bristol Bay coastline, including the communities of Dillingham and Togiak.
